threads.subject: Using Cursor's Agent
threads.preview: Cursor Cursor Agent ( https://cursor.com/docs/agent/overview ) can take on complex coding tasks, suc
threads.summary: The Cursor Team shared tips on using their Agent tool, which can handle complex coding tasks, and provided documentation links for features like context symbols, checkpoints, and command execution. The team outlined how to get the most out of Agent, including using "@" for specific context and defining rules for system-level instructions. No meeting is scheduled, but the information is available for reference on the Cursor website.
threads.last_body: Cursor Cursor Agent ( https://cursor.com/docs/agent/overview ) can take on complex coding tasks, such as creating features or fixing bugs end-to-end. You can use it in the sidepane with Cmd/Ctrl-I. To get the most out of Agent, here are some tips: * Use ‚Äú@‚Äù in your prompt ( https://cursor.com/docs/context/symbols#definitions ) to pull in specific context, such as specific files, websites, and git branches. * If you want to jump backwards in the Agent‚Äôs history, you can use checkpoints ( https://cursor.com/docs/agent/chat/checkpoints ) to revert changes. * Agent can run shell commands ( https://cursor.com/docs/agent/terminal ) as it works. You can also define command execution ( https://cursor.com/docs/agent/terminal#command-execution-modes ) rules. * With rules ( https://cursor.com/docs/context/rules#rules ) and /commands ( https://cursor.com/docs/agent/chat/commands ), you can configure system-level instructions and reusable workflows. * With cloud agents ( https://cursor.com/docs/cloud-agent ), you can spawn asynchronous agents that edit and run code in a remote environment. - Cursor Team Unsubscribe ( https://track.customer.io/unsubscribe/dgT_pwsBAPSntBzzp7QcAZreYtiKChCS8UINgrjOHg== )

threads.subject: Third-party security incident
threads.preview: OpenAI Logo ( https://openai.com/ ) Transparency is important to us, so we want to inform you about
threads.summary: OpenAI experienced a security incident through their data analytics provider, Mixpanel, which affected limited user data, including names, email addresses, and location information. No sensitive information like passwords or API keys was compromised. OpenAI has terminated its use of Mixpanel, is conducting additional security reviews, and is notifying impacted users, advising them to be cautious of potential phishing attempts.

summaries.summary: There was a security incident at OpenAI through their data provider Mixpanel, affecting some user data like names and emails. Fortunately, no sensitive info was compromised. OpenAI has stopped using Mixpanel and is reviewing security, also notifying impacted users to beware of phishing attempts.
